04716nam a22006255i 9781487511302DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875113027 a10.3138/97814875113022doi  a(DE-B1597)570815  a(OCoLC)1227700818  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aJL197.L53 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a324.271062231 aJeffrey, Brooke, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRoad to Redemption :bThe Liberal Party of Canada 2006-2019 /cBrooke Jeffrey. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 A Party on the Brink -- t2 Unanticipated Consequences: The 2006 Leadership Race -- t3 The Dion Era: Disappointment and Disarray -- t4 The Green Shift and the 2008 Election Debacle -- t5 Third Try: The Ignatieff Solution -- t6 The Near-Death Experience: The 2011 Election -- t7 Rebuilding and Renewal: Trudeau and the Liberal Way -- t8 Redemption: The 2015 Election -- t9 Trudeau Takes Charge: Creating a New Liberal Dynasty? -- t10 Second Chance: The 2019 Election -- tAppendix A: Federal Election Results 2006–2019 -- tAppendix B: Liberal Party Office Holders -- tAppendix C: List of Interviews -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite being described as the most successful political party in any western democracy, the Liberal Party of Canada experienced its worst electoral defeat in 2011. Reduced to third party status, some experts saw the Liberal Party of Canada as a spent force doomed to disappear from the Canadian political scene. And yet just four years later, the party surged ahead once more, winning one of the most decisive elections in Canadian history. Road to Redemption offers a detailed exploration of this stunning reversal. It begins by outlining weaknesses in the party’s organization and culture, weaknesses that existed long before the 2011 rout but were ignored while the party continued to win elections. Finally brought to light by the disastrous 2011 electoral campaign, these weaknesses were then systematically tackled by party elites and activists in a concerted effort to rebuild and restructure the party. Their efforts culminated in the state-of-the-art campaigns run by Justin Trudeau’s Liberals in 2015 and 2019. Brooke Jeffrey argues that the remarkable turnaround of 2015 confirms the Liberal Party’s exceptional ability to redefine itself and adapt to changing circumstances, a singular strength and the principal reason for its enduring appeal. Despite being reduced to a minority government in 2019, Jeffrey concludes that the Liberal Party and leader Justin Trudeau can take advantage of this second chance to further strengthen and consolidate the party’s position for years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aPolitical partieszCanada. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aCanadian federal elections.  aJustin Trudeau.  aLiberal Party of Canada (LPC).  aMichael Ignatieff.  aPolitical parties Canada.  aStephane Dion.  apolitics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751130240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487511302423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487511302/original  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3